                <p>A session is a way to store information to be used across multiple pages. Session variables store user information which can be used across multiple pages. Session variables last until the user closes the browser.</p>
                
                <h3>Starting a PHP Session</h3>
                <p>In PHP, a session can be started with the <strong>session_start()</strong> function. Session variables are set with the <code>$_SESSION</code> variable. Let's assume we have one webpage called <strong>example1.php</strong>. On this page, we will start a new PHP session and set session variables.</p>
                <pre class="text-white bg-black p-2"><code>&lt;?php
// Start the session
session_start();
?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

&lt;?php
// Set session variables
$_SESSION["uname"] = "shayan";
$_SESSION["upass"] = "hunter";
echo "Session variables are set.";
?&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
            
                <h3>Get PHP Session Variable Values</h3>
                <p>Now we will create a new page named <strong>example2.php</strong>. From this page, we will access the session variables we have set on the first page (example1.php).</p>
                <pre class="text-white bg-black p-2"><code>&lt;?php
session_start();
?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

&lt;?php
// Echo session variables that were set on previous page
echo "Favorite color is " . $_SESSION["uname"] . ".&lt;br&gt;";
echo "Favorite animal is " . $_SESSION["upass"] . ".";
?&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
                
                <p>We can also see all the session variables by using <strong>print_r($_SESSION).</strong></p>
                <pre class="text-white bg-black p-2"><code>&lt;?php
session_start();
?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

&lt;?php
print_r($_SESSION);
?&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
            
                <h3>Modifying a Session Variable</h3>
                <p>To modify a session variable, we just need to overwrite it.</p>
                <pre class="text-white bg-black p-2"><code>&lt;?php
session_start();
?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

&lt;?php
// to change a session variable, just overwrite it
$_SESSION["uname"] = "aakash";
print_r($_SESSION);
?&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
                
                <h3>Destroying a PHP Session</h3>
                <p>To delete all the session variables and destroy the session, we can use <strong>session_unset()</strong> and <strong>session_destroy()</strong>.</p>
                <pre class="text-white bg-black p-2"><code>&lt;?php
session_start();
?&gt;
&lt;!DOCTYPE html&gt;
&lt;html&gt;
&lt;body&gt;

&lt;?php
// remove all session variables
session_unset();

// destroy the session
session_destroy();
?&gt;

&lt;/body&gt;
&lt;/html&gt;</code></pre>
